[ ITIL 4 Overview ]
- What is ITIL? > A framework designed to manage service organizations.
- Why ITIL 4 exists > Help lead the 4h revolution of technology for mankind

- Value of Service Management

      |   > ITSM Helps all organizations, regardless of their industry or business sector, provide their IT services using the most efficient
      |   > Best practices & efficient operations.
      |   > Service Management is defined as a set of specialized organizational capabilities for enabling value to customers in the form of services.
      |   > Value is perceived and as such is based on the recipients perception. Value is subjective.
      |   > Perceived benefits, usefulness, and importance of "something"

	  v   

[ Service Value System (SVS) ] > Means of enabling value co-creation by facilitating outcomes that customers want to achieve,
      |   > without the customer having to manage specific costs and risks.
	  |	  > ITIL Concept that describes guiding principles
-
[Service Value System Components ]
     1. > Practices
     2. > Guiding Principles
      |     >[ 7 Guiding Principles ]
      |     Q: What is correct about the guiding principles?
      | > They are recommendatiosn that can guide an organization in all circumstances.
- Focus on Value: 
     > Deliver value to the stakeholders. (who are the Stakeholder?) the people that pay for service.
     > Understand what is truly of value to the service customer.
     > Understand customer experience for best service.
- Start Where You Are
     > Not start over without seeing what is currently available.
     > clear view of the current situation in order to build something new.

	 <>
- Progress Iteratively with feedback
 [Focuses on breaking work into smaller more manageable parts so it can be completed in a timely manner]
     > Organize in smaller, manageable sections that can be executed in a timely manner.
     > Iterations must be continously evaluated to ensure focus on value is still there as a guiding principle.
     > Request Feedback as you go along to uncover issues or failures.
     > Strive for MVPs (Minimum Valuable Products)

- Collaborate & Promote Visibility
     > Keep track of the flow of work in progress, identify bottlenecks and uncover waste.
     > Right employees for roles and responsibilities
          > Collaboration and communications
          > Subject to change based on stakeholders need.
     > involve, working with, include as many people as possible.
          > Best ideas come from unlikely sources.
          > Communicate as often as possible.
- Think & Work Holistically
     > All is connected. No service, practice, process, department or supplier stands alone.
     > clear communication, automation and a clear view of patterns
     > All acitivities align with the same focus on delivering value.
          > Consider the 4 dimensions of service management.
- Keep It Simple (& practical)
     > Use minimum number of steps for everything.
          > CDrating value, improving customer experience, task you do.  
     > Erase steps of no value so only value remains
     > Focusing on value is key to this step.
- Optimize & Automate
      > Standardize and streamline manual tasks by replacing humans with technology were possible.
      > Reduce Cost and human error
      > Improve efficiency of standard process so that humans can be used for more complex tasks.

     > Consider the 4 dismensions when determining how to optimize.

